In setup.py it copies the static files with this function:

def get_static_files(path):
    return [os.path.join(dirpath.replace("luigi/", ""), ext)
            for (dirpath, dirnames, filenames) in os.walk(path)
            for ext in ["*.html", "*.js", "*.css", "*.png",
                        "*.eot", "*.svg", "*.ttf", "*.woff", "*.woff2"]]


The URI folder was called URI.js, and the above function fails when it gets this folder extension

Do yo know why this is done twice: once before the wait and one after the wait:
```python
if self._done:
     return self._get_result()
```
I feel like it will work with that statement after the wait.

Yes, I also think it's better not to introduce `app-recreate.sh` but rather to stick to "duplicating"  instructions in `test_example_app.py`, as we have it done elsewhere. 

One additional benefit is getting nice explicit documentation generated out of `app.py` docstring.

@hachreak Note that we had discussed using shell scripts in the past for testing example apps -- this was actually the very first version I had -- but after a brief discussion we have agreed to go for  the `test_example_app.py` all-Pythonic approach. I refactored the same thing in the past :smile: see  the debate in https://github.com/inveniosoftware/invenio-records/pull/90. Can you please also amend similarly?

